                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origDate notAfter="1250" notBefore="1201">13th century, first half</origDate>. Origin unknown. According to an earlier librarian's note the manuscript might stem from a Danish monastery. However, no evidence for this exists and the supposition seems to be based on <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102535">Stephan Stephanius</persName>'s nationality. However, Stephanius bought many books on the continent, which makes it more likely that the manuscript is of French or German origin.</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>Early provenance unknown. During the early 17th century the manuscript belonged to <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102535"> Stephan Stephanius</persName>, whose hand has been identified on <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>. After his death the manuscript was purchased by <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102549">Magnus Gabriel de la Gardie</persName> and was then transferred to the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100059">Antiquities Archive</orgName>. The signum <quote>No 21</quote> on the <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/> refers to its placement in this institution. The signa <quote>96</quote> (<locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>) and <quote>94</quote> (<locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>) have not been identified.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Transferred from the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100059">Antiquities Archive</orgName> to the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">National Library</orgName> in <date when="1742"/>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
